<TITLE> Georgia and Russia open first land border crossing </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KAZBEGI, Georgia, Mar 1 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A mountain border crossing between Georgia and Russia, closed since July 2006, reopened on Monday in rare sign of cooperation after the former Soviet neighbours fought a brief war in 2008. The Verkhny Lars pass through the towering Caucasus mountains is effectively the only land crossing between Russia and Georgia, the others running through the Russian-backed rebel regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia. Analysts said the move was more economic than political, and would mostly benefit traders from Russia's landlocked economic ally Armenia. The checkpoints were opened from both sides early in the morning, but no vehicles had passed the border by midday Georgian time. Citizens of both countries require visas to cross the border. "The Daryal checkpoint, which was closed for several years, had been officially opened today," local police chief Georgy Gegechkori told journalists. Russia closed the border crossing in 2006 as ties between Moscow and the pro-Western government of President Mikheil Saakashvili soured. War broke out in August 2008 when US ally Georgia launched an assault on South Ossetia after days of skirmishes with rebels and years of escalating tension with the Kremlin, drawing a crushing Russian counter-strike. Russia cut air links with Georgia over the war, and Tblisi severed diplomatic ties when Moscow recognised the rebel territories as independent states in late August 2008. There were several charter flights between Tbilisi and Moscow over the January holiday period, but full air links have yet to resu
